[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] A presidential election was held in New Jersey on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1789 United States presidential election.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] The state legislature chose six representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] New Jersey, which had become the 3rd state on December 18, 1787, unanimously cast its 6 electoral votes for George Washington during its first presidential election.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-new-jersey] New Jersey was also the only state in the Union at the time where land-owning women were allowed to vote without the Nineteenth Amendment being in place.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-new-jersey] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] The **1790–91 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Senate elections occurred during the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1790 and 1791, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] In these elections, terms were up for the nine senators in Class 1.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] After the June 25, 1790 elections in Rhode Island.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] In these elections, the winners were seated before March 4, 1791; ordered by election date.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] In these regular elections, the winners were seated March 4, 1791; ordered by state.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] All of these elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] In these elections, the winners were seated after March 4, 1791, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] All of the senators from Connecticut were Pro-Administration through 1795.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Oliver Ellsworth was re-elected in 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] William Samuel Johnson resigned March 3, 1791, at the end of the 1st Congress and Roger Sherman was elected June 13, 1791, to finish the term.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Charles Carroll won re-election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 20.00%, or 15 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Senator, Tristam Dalton sought re-election but was eliminated before the third ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] The third ballot saw the election of George Cabot, who had been a member of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] The election in New York was held January 19, 1791, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Incumbent Philip Schuyler's term would expire March 3, 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] At the State election in April 1790, nominal Federalist majorities were elected to both houses of the 14th New York State Legislature, but many Federalists were friendly to the Democratic-Republican Governor George Clinton, party lines not being drawn very strictly then.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] The incumbent Philip Schuyler ran for re-election as the candidate of the Federalist Party.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] New York State Attorney General Aaron Burr was the candidate of the Democratic-Republican Party, but was at that time a rather moderate politician, opposing the ultras of both parties.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Burr was the choice of both the State Senate and the State Assembly, and was declared elected.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Schuyler was defeated despite the nominal majority of his party.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Many of the Federalists took the opportunity to show their disapproval of both Schuyler's haughtiness and the financial policies of Alexander Hamilton, the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Secretary of the Treasury and Schuyler's son-in-law.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Besides, the Livingston faction of the Federalist Party felt betrayed after the election of Rufus King over their candidate James Duane in 1789, and now allied themselves with Clinton and later became Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Obs.: Burr had a majority of 5 votes in the Assembly, but the exact number of votes is unclear.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] In 1791, the legislature failed to elect due to a disagreement on procedure.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] The seat would remain vacant until 1793.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Bradley and Moses Robinson were elected by the Vermont House of Representatives and Governor and Council in January 1791, anticipating Vermont's admission to the union.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Vermont was admitted as the 14th state on March 4, 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] The Senate had adjourned on March 3, at the completion of the 1st United States Congress; the 2nd United States Congress held a one-day session on March 4, and was not scheduled to convene again until October 24.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] As a result of this congressional schedule Bradley and Robinson had not been seated when the Vermont House of Representatives convened in early October, 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] At this legislative session, some members suggested that the January election of Bradley and Robinson had been premature, since Vermont had not yet been admitted to the union.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Bradley and Robinson volunteered to resign the credentials of their January elections; on October 17, the Governor and Council voted again, and selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] The House of Representatives then voted a second time, and also selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Bradley was selected for the "short term" (Class 3), which expired on March 3, 1795.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Robinson received the "long term" (Class 1), which expired on March 3, 1797.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] William Grayson died March 12, 1790, and John Walker was appointed to continue the term.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Future President James Monroe was elected in November 1790 to finish the term.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1790-united-states-senate-election-in-new-jersey] Monroe was re-elected in 1791 to the next term, as well.
[src:1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey/1824-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-jersey] New Jersey elected its members November 2, 1824.
